{"id":"1512.01234","submitter":"Daniel Szombati","authors":"D. B. Szombati, S. Nadj-Perge, D. Car, S. R. Plissard, E. P. A. M.\n  Bakkers, L. P. Kouwenhoven","title":"Josephson $\\varphi_{0}$-junction in nanowire quantum dots","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Nat. Phys. 12 (2016) 568","doi":"10.1038/nphys3742","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Josephson effect describes supercurrent flowing through a junction\nconnecting two superconducting leads by a thin barrier [1]. This current is\ndriven by a superconducting phase difference $\\phi$ between the leads. In the\npresence of chiral and time reversal symmetry of the Cooper pair tunneling\nprocess [2] the current is strictly zero when $\\phi$ vanishes. Only if these\nunderlying symmetries are broken the supercurrent for $\\phi=0$ may be finite\n[3-5]. This corresponds to a ground state of the junction being offset by a\nphase $\\phi_{0}$, different from 0 or $\\pi$. Here, we report such a Josephson\n$\\phi_{0}$-junction based on a nanowire quantum dot. We use a quantum\ninterferometer device in order to investigate phase offsets and demonstrate\nthat $\\phi_{0}$ can be controlled by electrostatic gating. Our results have\npossible far reaching implications for superconducting flux and phase defined\nquantum bits as well as for exploring topological superconductivity in quantum\ndot systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Dec 2015 21:00:02 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 23 Feb 2016 09:32:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-07-28"}
